Cryptocurrency Legal Status by Country

1. Countries Where Cryptocurrency is Accepted as Official Currency (Legal Tender)
El Salvador
Year: 2021
Cryptocurrency: Bitcoin (BTC)
Status: Bitcoin is legal tender alongside the US Dollar. It can be used for tax payments, salaries, goods, and services.
Note: First country in the world to adopt cryptocurrency as official currency.
Central African Republic (CAR)
Year: 2022
Cryptocurrency: Bitcoin
Status: Adopted Bitcoin as legal tender, but later repealed in 2023.
Current Status: No longer legal tender.
Summary: Only El Salvador currently recognizes cryptocurrency as official currency.

2. Countries Where Cryptocurrency is Recognized as an Asset / Property / Investment
These countries do not treat cryptocurrency as currency, but allow holding, trading, and investing.
United States: Classified as property; taxed under capital gains; regulated by SEC, CFTC, and IRS.
Japan: Recognized as legal property; exchange regulations enforced.
India: Treated as Virtual Digital Asset (VDA); taxed at 30% on profits with 1% TDS.
Canada: Considered a commodity; taxable; crypto ETFs approved.
Australia: Treated as property; capital gains tax applies.
Germany: Considered private money; tax-free if held over one year.
United Kingdom: Classified as crypto asset; regulated by FCA; capital gains tax applies.
Switzerland: Treated as asset; highly crypto-friendly.
Singapore: Recognized as digital payment token; no capital gains tax for individuals.
United Arab Emirates: Legal asset; regulated; Dubai and Abu Dhabi are crypto hubs.

South Africa â€“ Cryptocurrency Status
Legal Status: Cryptocurrency is legal as an asset, not as currency.
Regulation:
The South African Reserve Bank (SARB) does not recognize crypto as legal tender.
Cryptocurrency is treated as financial property.
Exchanges must comply with anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CTF) regulations.

Taxation:
	The South African Revenue Service (SARS) treats crypto as capital gains or income, depending on transaction type.
Usage: Allowed for trading, investment, and payments, but merchants are not required to accept it.
Summary: Legal to hold, trade, and invest; not official currency.

3. Countries Where Cryptocurrency is Banned or Restricted
China: Trading and mining banned.
Afghanistan: Cryptocurrency banned.
Bangladesh: Illegal.
Egypt: Restricted.
Nepal: Illegal.

4. Summary 
Official Currency - El Salvador
Previously Legal Tender - Central African Republic
Legal as Asset - United States, Japan, India, Canada, Australia, Germany, United Kingdom, Switzerland, Singapore, United Arab Emirates
Banned / Restricted - China, Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Egypt, Nepal




